  "text": "Cost is also a prime consideration when choosing intervention options. In an economic analysis, Wilson and Datta 77 predicted the cost/ benefit of implementing Taiji as part of a falls prevention program in a typical nursing home. They estimated an annual program direct cost of just under $9,000 annually for two classes per week of Yang-style Taiji instruction. Using risk ratios derived from the FISCIT studies and 2001 medical cost data, they predicted a net institutional saving of $1,274.43 per participant per year in falls prevention. Although this analysis suggests economic feasibility, Wilson and Datta [CITATION_1] cautioned facility administrators that confirming empirical evidence of Taiji's utility within a nursing home setting was advisable before program adoption. The work by Wilson and Datta [CITATION_2] can be used as a model to predict cost effectiveness when planning new programming.",
